\pard\plain \fi720\sl288\slmult1\ltrch\loch {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Love can only land if it is looked for. This was one life lesson which stayed steady across all her years. A love sent must land, or else it wheels about, and like a shorebird blown to sea it will panic, tire, then drown. The only way to avoid that grief is to never love, but that is difficult to do, so the next best thing is to never love unless it\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s looked for.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93Wait until the beloved }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 wants}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  it,\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8221\'94 is what she preached, even if she could not practice it. She was the Impartial Third, and being impartial, quintessentially so, she loved everyone and everything intensely. It was her fate that the dark hurt of unrequited love should attended her wanderings. A grief upon grief, for there was another life lesson which stayed steady across all her years, though it could not be called a lesson yet, for she never did learn how watch those whom she loved make mistakes. }
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She stood now at the edge of a barren plateau. She contemplated the shape her skull might make after bursting on a sandstone stump far below. And oh, how the rest of her body would tumble before dislocating every joint in that distant riverbed. The red of the iron rich clay would hide the spill of blood, but her white robes would wear it well. She would be that aged woman flyswatted at the base of a cliff. She had seen this fate.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She had seen how, on some future day, a chance rain would wash over the black peaks behind and sweep her bones out into the broader expanse of the desert. There, she would join two armies who had, this very morning, slaughtered each other. She had loved them, and they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d slaughtered each other. Thousands lay scattered in the orange sand, dark lumps, wastes of mother\u8217\'92s milk, spears stuck into faces like overgrown toothpicks. Why? Pick the reason. Perhaps some Lord desired grazing lands which belonged to his neighbors. Perhaps grazing lands were overgrazed, and now all must contest for scraps. A simple insult might have forced this day, or jealousy, or a pattern of abuse inflicted on a child who became king, growing him into a tyrant. What did the cause matter when the consequences were the same? Rape. Base enslavement. Slaughter. And oh, it was getting worse all over the world, all while the prayers of the oppressor were addressed to same god as the oppressed. She could do nothing about it but plant cautionary tales and watch as her words were twisted into the exact opposite of what she\u8217\'92d meant.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Those square battle standards were planted in the sand }{\f1\fs24\b0\i1\cf1 this morning}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 , and already, the sun had bleached the color. One full day of light working on weak dye, and it was no longer possible to tell who was who. Those honored sons and daughters could not speak their names, not with gusts of sand piling into their mouths.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She loved them as her own children, and there was sand piling into their mouths.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 \loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8220\'93It must finish!\u8221\'94 she said to the biting wind. \u8220\'93Or else, return to the way it was!\u8221\'94}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The wind knew her meaning, for it still carried the aroma of wildflowers in its breath. That riverbank far below was once flush with flowers, endless fields of thumb-sized bells, swinging, blue and pink. She longed for that sweet scent to stick to her clothes again, and oh, how she would delight in the excitement every little butterfly and bee. Red-headed birds chirped in glee as they hunted those crazed swarms, while the meat of those birds fed foxes, and all of them, at different stages of life, from womb to carrion corpse, fed lizards. The meat of the lizards fed eagles, and on the circle went. The Creative First and Destructive Second had measured out those fates, and as the Impartial Third, it had been her duty to cut them. She\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d cut them halfway down the difference. Her duty, her shame, because the only things growing on the surface now were lichens.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Brown, fuzzy rags, those lichens, sitting on the sand. Interspersed as they were amongst the dead, they\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d soaked up too much blood. Too many of their number would die. This day was the first link in a chain of catastrophes which would see their species extinct in less than twenty years.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She stepped off the cliff.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Her white robes clung to her body as she fell. The wind ripped tears from her eyes while the whistling in her ears promised peace.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Death would be better for her.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Assuredly.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Better for her, but only her. For those she loved, she needed to see the day through.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She clenched her fists and swerved out of her fall with the power of flight. She zipped through the red rock valley. She followed the course of the fossilizing river through the sweep of bodies buried in the great dream of sacrifice. Each honored son and daughter believed that their sacrifice would make a difference. If only they could see the red line of fire which scored the horizon, marking another outbreak of war, and would burn for days. A roiling cloud of smoke spread out above it, the ashes of a city, an immensity so great that it could be called a god in its own right, deserving of a name. L}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 ightning flashed inside its stomach. On came the distant drum of sequent thunder, and oh, how it mocked those sacrificial dreams.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She bit her lip to keep from weeping.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She wiped her cheek clean from the stain of tears.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She bit her lip hard now, because those below were dead, and elsewhere more were dying, and she desired pity for herself.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Appalling.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Unconscionable.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She sped towards the setting sun.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Far beyond the sprawl of embattled dead, she saw her destination: a stub of table rock. It was a natural formation, but unique enough, and its isolation amidst a flat expanse made it impossible to miss. Once directly above it}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 , she took a deep breath, then spoke a charm to trap a wide bubble of air around her. Then, she punched straight up into the sky at speed which would rip the feathers off a bird.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 In half an instant, she was floating in the middle reaches of the atmosphere. Here she stopped to settle her nerves, as swimming in the peachy glow of sundown clouds always calmed her. She poked her head through a pinkish puff to spy the sunny side of the world as it curved away in shades of green. Streaks of shine marked the Hrkan delta. The Creative First built out that alluvial plain with a word she\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d cobbled together from invented syllables, and she worked there now, hoping to inspire a nascent civilization to pull themselves up out of the mud.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 To the west, the desert curved away into night. A shifting layer of blurring cloud and smoke obscured a smattering of tiny fires on the cold surface. The Destructive Second lurked there, cracking open mountains to draw up heat. Her armies were never in want of replenishment, which suggested the primacy of her cause.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The Impartial Third drifted below the bottom of her cloud to look again upon those honored sons and daughters, whom she loved. From this height, they were a line of flakes spilling off the broken walls of a gray city to the east. To the north were dead forests, slashed and burned, cleared to make more room for cattle, who grazed swarming multitudes. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 All principle river in this region was dammed, trapping a lake whose waterline lay far below the yellow stains of its highest mark. To the south, a line of bare mountains rumpled up the rifts of tectonic plates like festering wounds, and behold, there on the western edge of all that scabby earthflesh, standing on the highest peak, was the God of all creation. He, a fallen star, four pointed, glimmered brightly}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 . From this height, she could blot out His sparkle with her thumb.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 It was time.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She flew straight up through the warm gradations of the sunset to find the black of night, where the chill gripped her. The object she sought lay somewhere above. She had placed it there in the upper reaches, where the pull of the earth was weak.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She slowed to a drift. Her gray braids slacked, then brushed her neck as they drifted past her cheeks. Her robes lifted off her skin like a waking flower.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She drifted upwards still, towards the object of her desire, a thing she\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92d found many years ago, a thing she\u8217\'92d kept a secret for a moment such as this, a thing which she could not see even though she knew it was right there in front of her now, humbling her. If she weren\u8217\'92t careful she might collide with it.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She stopped. The skirt of her robes flowed past her like a white sail, then brushed up against some invisible protrusion. The thing was there, still embedded in the void. It only ever became visible if she focused on her grief.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She focused on those honored sons and daughters. She focused on her own broken body. She dwelled in the world\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s ignorance of her love.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Tears welled in her eyes, and through this blurring lens she saw an edge shimmer. At once, the fullness of the thing she sought shifting into being.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 What it was, she had no name for, so she called it Black. It was a jagged black stone, chaotically pinched, the shape of a wound, a spiky complex of scar contractures marring the swathe of stars behind it. Its size was impossible to say, as the Black was of a substance which defied all size comparison; it would appear larger next to objectively larger things, for it could reach straight into her mind and impose a feeling: small, insignificant, purposeless. It\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s essence swallowed hers.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The Black turned, slowly, through its tempted orbit. It turned to reveal a flat, cylindrical head, a shape suggesting it should slot into something greater. For her purposes, that head would serve as hammer.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She floated around the Black\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s chunky body to take up a position behind it. By now, her tears were ice, and her eyes were frozen open. She could hardly move her fingers. She held out her palm, and spoke a word of impulse, then pushed.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The moment her skin contacted the stone, then pull the impulse out of her.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Her mind ran flush with disjointed visions of her childhood, centering on the face of the mother who abused her. Her first love, who never saw in her what she saw in herself. The despair which led her to be chosen as the Impartial Third, inserting her into the written word. Now, history, as she had seen it. The first king and the first queen, and the first demagogue; the first sailing ship and the first shipwreck; the first minted silver coin and the first imitation of it, a thin bit of copper washed in pewter; the ever-present urge to horde; the night she gained the sight; anatomy lessons with the flayed; the long charter of the fleshcraft guild; the temptations of priests; the origins of debt; the operations of war; the shock of famine; King Sixa\loch\af0\hich\af0\dbch\af0\uc1\u8217\'92s plan to pot the desert with wells; the explosion of Mount Volgi which poisoned half the world; the beginning of table manners; the wars of religion; the wars of hate; the selfishness, the loneliness, and more. All of it. The Black pulled out all of her grief to sustain its hungry flight. When it parted from her touch, she was naught but a yawning stupor, barely able to even sip on her bubble of air.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 Shortly after, the Black smashed into the atmosphere. It fell into the clouds, then out of them. When its tumble obscured the shinia as it fell upon the God of all creation, Him, the fallen star.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 The}{\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1  impact shook the earth.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 A fireball the size of a mushroomed up into the. A shockwave swept the sky clean, even as it dragged a shade of dust behind it. When this wave found the sea, it steamed the waters, ignited a magnificent phytoplankton bloom, thousands of miles long, whirling in a gyre.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 The soundlessness of space muted her sigh of awe.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 Cold gripped her lungs.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0\cf1 She sensed the stretching of time, the thinness of her life. }{\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She wondered how long her body would last amongst the stars. She wondered how long she would cast her shadow upon the world. And last, She imagined a child hearing the story of the Impartial Third who killed God, and oh, how she wished that child would stare up into the night to look for her.}
\par\plain {\f0\fs24\b0\i0 She breathed in her last, held it, and died.}}